 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=q66stang>Q66stang</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 19<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/9/03 9:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=85>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Show us your numbers. Put up or shut up.</span><hr size=1> Nuclaeon<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> When plasma interacts with a solid, a layer called the sheath forms which accelerates ions toward the surface of the plate and pushes away electrons. These ions will implant themselves in the pusher plate. This effect is so fast that the plate will become saturated within the first few blasts. This could be a complication on Orion; however, it does not seem to compromise the strength of the divertor tokamak reactors so it may not be such a huge problem.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Isn’t the tokamak magnetically confined? And are not the materials used in the confinement walls neutron loaded, which for both of these solutions require an ample source of power to maintain? <br>
<br>
In addition to maintaining equilibrium physics, additional power is required for density and temperature profile control in order to maintain optimum physics performance.<br>
<br>
There is also the adding of impurities to the reactor to reduce the maximum heat flux at the divertor. And lets not forget a constant velocity of water coolant.<br>
<br>
All of these precautionary measures, and more, are required to efficiently operate a tokamak reactor to about 75 –90% efficiency, and still the materials inside the reactor that make up the structural central column have a lifespan of only 4 years.<br>
<br>
Has all this been taken into account for the Orions pusher plate?<br>
