<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> You argue that George and Freeman Dyson would not guarrentee that the design would work is proof that it was a failure. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
No, I’m arguing that the nuclear detonations will destroy the pusher plate assembly long before Orion ever reaches it’s destination. I don’t see much else wrong with the engineering of the craft.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Their knoledge, experiments, and research done while doing the project for ten years suggested that it would work</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I see that as a lot of hand waving.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Reactor containment vessels are exposed to intense neutron bombardment continuously for decades. Neutrons are more likely to transmut materials then Gammas, yet the containment vessels stay sound. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
There is a big difference between a reactor and Orion.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Most of the bomb's radiation would not encounter the ship, only a small portion would be projected toward the ship</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
If only a small portion, how does the pulse propel Orion forward? I think you greatly underestimate radiation exposure to the ship and the crew.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> activity levels would die down to safe levels in a few hours as the nuclides produced would have short half-lives.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
A few hours? Tell me, what materials do they use in the bombs?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Over time the pusher plate would degrade from plasma and radiation, but it could be replaced when wear became too great.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The degradation to the plate would be a lot sooner than expected.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> And it seems like you have some basic information on radioactive decay. I don't get what point you are making here.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The point is simple – Orion will not work due to greatly underestimated damage that will result from nuclear detonations. Few here are willing to understand and accept that. They would much rather jump on the bandwagon even after admitting they know very little about the subject matter.<br>
